WEBVTT

00:02.849 --> 00:12.320
The best records that I know of, we have of how we got to where we are, is by writing.

00:12.640 --> 00:14.723
Not necessarily in books, but writing.

00:15.924 --> 00:32.063
And the history of all that has been accomplished, really, is what we have learned by deciphering or reading or studying skeletons, etc., but

00:32.448 --> 00:36.194
Certainly, the written record has been exceptionally important.

00:40.480 --> 00:46.789
I'm interested in the phenomenon of saving writings.

00:47.771 --> 00:53.038
Obviously, I don't have many important writings from the age of a cuneiform.

00:53.519 --> 01:00.970
I just have one tablet, so when my students come, I should show them a clay tablet that was written 3,500 years ago.

01:02.182 --> 01:18.925
I have one piece of Egyptian ... It's an interesting piece of one of their scrolls of papyrus.

01:18.945 --> 01:21.248
It's also very old.

01:21.268 --> 01:30.501
I never thought anybody could read it, including several Egyptian students that I've had.

01:31.122 --> 01:32.844
So that's a little before our time.

01:33.705 --> 01:37.409
And a few manuscripts, one time or another.

01:38.090 --> 01:43.756
Mostly, I guess, all I've got are the books that have been important in the development of medicine.

01:45.257 --> 01:58.952
From that time to this, that I've been able to find and enjoy looking at, studying how they were made and where they've been, if possible.

02:00.164 --> 02:10.317
and learning what it was that they gave to us in the formation of the practice of medicine, if you like.

02:10.337 --> 02:13.942
The science, the art, the problems.

02:14.002 --> 02:20.750
Did you start collecting prior to becoming a physician?

02:21.331 --> 02:21.611
No.

02:23.694 --> 02:26.037
Prior to becoming a physician,

02:26.303 --> 02:31.449
I was a medical student, and once I was a physician, I was doing research.

02:32.370 --> 02:48.568
And there, of course, was involved with reading records of other investigators who had worked in the same field, which is, in part, learning the history of my special function of the intestinal tract.

02:48.588 --> 02:55.956
So that, you know, you start looking at that, and then you develop into looking at other things as well.

02:56.189 --> 03:01.976
I wonder what brought you to the collecting of the book.

03:02.777 --> 03:05.160
Well, that had nothing to do with any reality.

03:06.241 --> 03:26.044
A local book dealer gave a talk to our library association, and he had for sale a copy of The Sages, which was the first modern anatomy book.

03:27.661 --> 03:29.924
That was published in 1542.

03:31.527 --> 03:35.633
But prior to that time, anatomy was really gross.

03:35.833 --> 03:38.838
It was impossible to be useful.

03:40.360 --> 03:57.465
It so happened that he had an artist who obviously studied his dissections with him, and who was able to draw the anatomy of the human being.

03:57.614 --> 03:59.476
that is as good as any modern.

03:59.496 --> 03:59.896
Really?

04:00.116 --> 04:04.680
Well, not in polar details, but yes.

04:05.901 --> 04:13.168
He had woodblocks prepared, and published this.

04:13.188 --> 04:22.997
Now, there were several contemporary anatomists, one of whom, you might just jot that this down as a site.

04:23.597 --> 04:26.440
Eustachius was a

04:27.432 --> 04:36.503
Italian physician who actually had prepared wood blocks.

04:36.523 --> 04:37.284
Not wood blocks.

04:37.304 --> 04:41.049
I think it was engraving steel or copper.

04:42.250 --> 04:46.355
And he had done dissections, and he had learned a good bit of anatomy.

04:47.937 --> 04:55.887
And he had been to see the pope who was sick, and on his way back home he died, whatever it was the pope had, and nobody ever saw.

04:56.440 --> 05:06.469
The illustrations that he made, except a few of the kidney, but the gross anatomy was published in 1714, I think it was.

05:07.249 --> 05:20.681
So Eustachius, though he was a good anatomist, and really had done a hell of a good job, he was unfortunately not working on it.

05:20.701 --> 05:25.705
There was one other, I think it was a Frenchman.

05:26.714 --> 05:40.249
But he also would have published before Mercedes, except he was working with another doctor and had an argument.

05:41.170 --> 05:43.973
The other doctor sued him, and the court would not let him publish.

05:44.833 --> 05:53.683
So the book that should have come out in 1539 didn't come out till 1546 after Mercedes.

05:53.849 --> 05:59.496
So, you know, that's one of those very funny stories.

05:59.997 --> 06:01.218
It should be.

06:01.238 --> 06:03.401
Is there a bibliography in your specialty?

06:03.421 --> 06:05.724
You pretty much have had to develop your own.

06:05.744 --> 06:06.805
Oh, God, yes.

06:06.825 --> 06:08.027
Oh, I mean, in internal medicine.

06:08.047 --> 06:11.772
This is your... Oh, it's bibliography.

06:11.792 --> 06:14.615
In every field of medicine.

06:14.775 --> 06:15.296
Yeah.

06:15.416 --> 06:18.220
But, I mean, even in the old books, under the classic books, yeah.

06:18.260 --> 06:20.903
Here, for instance, is a...

06:22.148 --> 06:23.850
A book that lists.

06:24.551 --> 06:30.357
And may I?

06:30.457 --> 06:36.824
You'd have to know what you're looking for, but, you know, there are many lists.

06:36.864 --> 06:41.309
Tell me a little bit about how long have you been practicing medicine, Doctor?

06:41.329 --> 06:50.839
I graduated from medical school in 1937, Philadelphia, interned in Los Angeles County General Hospital for two years.

06:51.697 --> 07:00.208
Went back to Penn and Jefferson, did research, did graduate work, and was teaching.

07:01.510 --> 07:09.961
All mixed up until 1942, and some kind of thing broke out in Europe.

07:10.081 --> 07:15.107
I felt that I had to do something with it.

07:16.249 --> 07:17.831
And we had our oldest son.

07:19.073 --> 07:20.134
Everything was fine.

07:21.532 --> 07:29.402
So I told my wife, and I said, look, we've got to do whatever we can.

07:29.422 --> 07:31.986
So I got in the Army.

07:34.168 --> 07:36.732
And are you a Californian?

07:36.792 --> 07:43.280
Well, I was a Philadelphian until 1960, and then became a Californian and moved here.

07:43.501 --> 07:47.806
Oh, so you've been here 30 years.

07:47.866 --> 07:50.249
Well, you were collecting books then before you came here?

07:50.309 --> 07:50.830
Not really.

07:52.312 --> 07:57.798
Well, I was collecting titles and information, but not actual books.

07:58.579 --> 08:01.042
And my first book was this, Vesalius.

08:01.122 --> 08:07.209
The Vesalius, you got out here in California.

08:07.289 --> 08:08.731
Yeah.

08:09.812 --> 08:15.659
I was just wondering at what point you decided to become a collector.

08:15.679 --> 08:17.141
It's hard to say.

08:17.181 --> 08:20.665
I went to see the Vesalius.

08:22.045 --> 08:24.768
And I felt a great kinship.

08:26.650 --> 08:31.355
And next thing you know, I bought the goddamn thing.

08:31.375 --> 08:33.998
And from then on, I guess I was a collector.

08:34.638 --> 08:38.462
This is at a local bookstore, Dawson's, if and so on.

08:38.482 --> 08:43.768
Well, we'd like that, except we'd deal with it.

08:44.088 --> 08:50.034
And you look like you have some extraordinary, are all the books illustrative books, basically?

08:50.054 --> 08:50.635
No, no.

08:52.268 --> 08:57.613
And so your focus has been to try to document the history of your profession, I guess, in a phrase.

08:58.854 --> 08:59.475
That's right.

08:59.495 --> 09:03.659
And how thoroughly would you say you've been able to do it?

09:04.000 --> 09:08.364
I think reasonably well.

09:10.606 --> 09:15.811
Do you feel that, you know, there's this illness they call biblio-mania?

09:16.031 --> 09:17.793
I approach it at times.

09:20.075 --> 09:21.837
I think you'll have difficulty in

09:22.323 --> 09:27.709
separating me from the bibliomaniacs.

09:27.729 --> 09:34.997
But... Being a professional diagnostician, could you tell me a little bit about what are the symptoms of this disease?

09:37.180 --> 09:50.575
Well, I guess an overwhelming desire to hold books, look at old books, and... And... Presumably, you could...

09:50.993 --> 10:01.608
These are very valuable items, and I presume you could get a later edition, which would be... What is it to have the first edition?

10:01.628 --> 10:07.656
Well, to have the first is to get a look at how this started.

10:07.676 --> 10:18.992
And if you're looking at the history and development of any particular art, economic policy, information of any kind,

10:20.221 --> 10:32.592
I think it's always important to have an idea how it started and how it developed, so that part of it is a desire to see how it began.

10:34.854 --> 10:36.636
What do you hope to do with the library?

10:37.737 --> 10:42.261
That's something we haven't really completely decided.

10:45.023 --> 10:46.925
I don't know for sure.

10:46.945 --> 10:47.845
You're enjoying it.

10:47.886 --> 10:49.587
That's the important part.

10:50.377 --> 11:03.594
Alan indicated that you've been involved in local book collecting groups and stuff like that, and you might be able to give us some sense of book collecting in Los Angeles.

11:05.296 --> 11:12.205
Every big city that I know of has a group of people with the syllabus.

11:12.225 --> 11:20.215
They look all over the city, and all classes and all styles.

11:21.275 --> 11:28.124
Unfortunately, the field that I chose and was interested in happens to be one that was started long ago.

11:31.089 --> 11:36.276
The first of the books, you know, what am I going to say?

11:38.058 --> 11:42.404
Egyptian papyri, which I don't happen to have one, I've described.

11:44.387 --> 11:51.096
I guess this is surgery for stone, bladder stone, 3,500 years ago.

11:51.937 --> 11:55.121
Yeah, it's amazing.

11:55.141 --> 11:57.564
Did they perform surgery for the virus?

12:00.667 --> 12:13.122
Well, if you had a diagnosis and you didn't have any good x-rays, but if the patient passed red urine and had severe pain at a certain time, you would guess that that was it.

12:14.623 --> 12:16.105
And if you got him drunk enough,

12:16.473 --> 12:22.162
had some people hold them down and get the bladder open and get it out.

12:23.484 --> 12:25.907
And some of them got recovered.

12:27.790 --> 12:29.993
So you took your chances, I guess.

12:30.214 --> 12:31.576
Well, yeah.

12:33.238 --> 12:37.004
You didn't operate on the king until you'd done a lot.

12:38.106 --> 12:45.737
But, you know, that's... There are quite a few

12:46.173 --> 12:49.297
Philadelphia is quite a book collecting area.

12:50.359 --> 12:50.739
Oh, yes.

12:50.839 --> 12:52.481
I've spent a lot of time down there.

12:52.501 --> 12:55.365
Well, you know the College of Physicians, of course.

12:55.645 --> 12:55.946
Of course, yes.

12:56.066 --> 13:01.393
And my professor would be, he broke land.

13:02.775 --> 13:12.788
He had a great collection that we students would be invited to his own exams, you know what?

13:17.425 --> 13:25.073
And, of course, the College of Physicians is all great.

13:25.894 --> 13:28.036
Are you interested mostly in medicine?

13:28.717 --> 13:34.223
No, I'm interested in books, and not just books, but manuscripts, anything.

13:34.823 --> 13:38.187
I'm really interested in collecting, and the passion.

13:38.227 --> 13:40.329
So you're collecting collectors and stuff?

13:40.349 --> 13:41.650
Yeah, that's it.

13:41.670 --> 13:47.196
You've got it, and it makes some sense out of the whole thing, and tells some interesting stories.

13:48.020 --> 13:54.487
In your field, have you pretty much stayed close to that focus, or have you strayed?

13:54.847 --> 13:56.229
Medicine, yes.

13:56.790 --> 14:00.714
Gastroenterology, no.

14:00.734 --> 14:03.637
I mean, strayed through the field of medicine.

14:04.658 --> 14:10.264
Have you acquired pretty much out here, or have you traveled to hunt for the things?

14:10.284 --> 14:17.352
Well, I have hunted for things, but I will say that once I got started,

14:18.142 --> 14:25.249
sellers hunted for me, and it was very quick, very short time for me.

14:25.450 --> 14:45.010
Harry Levinson was the one who sold me to Vesalius, and within a couple of months, one of Jake Zaper, who was the other bookseller, called me up, and he has a wonderful book.

14:45.513 --> 14:49.478
So, you know, Jake is quite an institution out here.

14:49.498 --> 14:50.018
Yes.

14:50.038 --> 14:53.282
So he was second in line.

14:53.603 --> 14:56.166
But then after that, they were all there.

14:56.186 --> 15:05.356
And I gather, because it's such a specialized field, there aren't that many people who are collecting, or would you say that there are quite a few?

15:05.376 --> 15:07.980
There are quite a few, I think.

15:08.821 --> 15:15.148
You know, before I was collecting, I had, well, the first edition of

15:15.685 --> 15:18.468
in my medical textbook.

15:19.509 --> 15:22.152
Why, I don't know.

15:22.172 --> 15:24.455
I never looked at it.

15:24.475 --> 15:33.645
But I'd seen it in a second-hand store in Philadelphia, and it was $4.50 or something, so I bought it.

15:35.888 --> 15:40.112
You know, and I think there are many, many documents in the government.

15:40.152 --> 15:45.118
Do you enjoy the collection as much today as you did when you started it in 1960?

15:45.402 --> 15:47.224
It's not the kind of thing you get bored of.

15:47.285 --> 15:50.549
It's not the acquisition that gives you the satisfaction.

15:50.569 --> 15:57.899
No, I enjoy looking through it, see what I have on this or that.

15:57.919 --> 16:00.042
Do you learn anything from his old books?

16:00.062 --> 16:02.044
Anything?

16:02.064 --> 16:02.825
I don't think so.

16:03.086 --> 16:15.122
Learn how things develop, and also see how time changes things, and how much of what we do now is very similar to what they did then.

16:15.693 --> 16:27.511
realized that there was a dean at UCLA named Sherman Mellinkoff.

16:27.531 --> 16:36.225
He is really, he started as a gastroenterologist, but he, next thing you know, became dean of medicine medical school.

16:38.709 --> 16:44.097
Very thoughtful, very bright, very capable guy, and he

16:46.203 --> 17:16.075
about a year ago published a paper in general, in the General Environmental Association, which I have to find because I've lost my copy of it, in which he pointed out that of the thousands of herbs and preparations that we know about, and the many hundreds that we have studied and used

17:16.460 --> 17:19.303
Those in orange.

17:20.744 --> 17:23.386
There's six left.

17:25.248 --> 17:26.629
Yeah, just six.

17:28.491 --> 17:30.453
The aspirin comes from the willow tree.

17:31.414 --> 17:34.637
The flying one comes from some goddamn tree in South America.

17:37.740 --> 17:40.922
Digitalis comes from the foxglove.

17:44.005 --> 17:45.647
That's about a four or not.

17:45.667 --> 17:45.927
That's right.

17:46.497 --> 18:07.411
All the rest are chemicals that have been possibly present after some of these, but changed completely.

18:07.431 --> 18:11.678
There was just a piece in the New York Times about some

18:12.316 --> 18:22.129
There's a ewe, a tree that they harvest up in the Pacific Northwest, which apparently they're finding successful in the treatment of something.

18:22.149 --> 18:22.890
Did you see that?

18:22.910 --> 18:23.530
Some cancer, yeah.

18:23.550 --> 18:24.572
Yeah.

18:24.592 --> 18:26.534
And there was never any use for the tree.

18:26.594 --> 18:29.378
Now all of a sudden— Oh, they used it for something, I can tell you.

18:32.041 --> 18:34.404
All of these things were used for something.

18:38.189 --> 18:40.332
Every grandmother had a collection.

18:41.662 --> 18:45.706
Do you have an old grandmother?

18:45.726 --> 18:47.268
Margaret chamomile tea.

18:47.288 --> 18:47.768
Yes.

18:48.829 --> 18:50.811
And the yucca plants you had?

18:50.911 --> 18:51.372
Yes.

18:52.733 --> 18:56.297
Well, they all had a collection of dried things and what have you.

18:56.317 --> 19:03.624
They used, when you had something, they rubbed it on your chest or gave it to you a drink or what have you.

19:03.644 --> 19:07.648
Some of them made you feel good, especially if they put it in wine.

19:07.668 --> 19:10.791
And, uh, this is, uh,

19:11.581 --> 19:14.745
It's been every single culture.

19:15.105 --> 19:15.806
That's another thing.

19:15.846 --> 19:16.767
It's a general thing.

19:16.787 --> 19:18.790
Let me show you some things.

19:18.810 --> 19:22.094
Yeah, I'd love to sit down.

19:22.114 --> 19:23.956
Let me show you that.

19:23.976 --> 19:25.598
Oh, good, good, good.

19:25.618 --> 19:33.248
This has nothing to do with medicine.

19:33.408 --> 19:35.911
This is the Egyptian... Oh, that's the firing animal.

19:35.931 --> 19:36.111
Go there.

19:36.131 --> 19:38.554
Now, there's the procession.

19:38.574 --> 19:39.816
They're pulling this wagon.

19:40.454 --> 19:46.080
See the mommies and they're pulling through the street and he was a priest as part of the procession.

19:46.480 --> 19:47.441
Is that part of the same?

19:47.581 --> 19:48.062
Yeah.

19:49.443 --> 19:52.506
And this was about 3,200 years ago.

19:52.566 --> 19:58.573
You know, it's something, isn't it?

20:00.274 --> 20:00.695
Crazy.

20:00.715 --> 20:02.877
It's preserved pretty decently, isn't it?

20:05.339 --> 20:07.862
And you said, well, I dug it out of the ground, you know, really.

20:08.264 --> 20:10.987
He said you had a chileiform tablet, I guess.

20:11.087 --> 20:12.969
Oh, yeah, yeah, yeah.

20:16.353 --> 20:17.054
Oh, yeah, yeah.

20:17.134 --> 20:23.361
For instance, this is one that I bought a few years ago.

20:23.381 --> 20:26.845
Oh, that's from China.

20:27.106 --> 20:29.168
Yeah, that's one.

20:29.188 --> 20:30.309
Well, you know them well.

20:30.390 --> 20:33.193
These are not good news.

20:33.213 --> 20:33.553
You see?

20:34.815 --> 20:35.976
Well, if you look at it,

20:37.255 --> 20:40.038
